{"/service/ndnp/sdhi/batch_sdhi_imbe_ver01/data/sn96090237/00340581027/1913121901/1271.xml":{"full_text":"VILLA TAKES LEAD\nHIGH HANDED METHODS ARE IN\nFORCE IN CHICHUHUA BV\nFRANCISCO VILLA.\nWHOLESALE SEIZURES MADE\nDepartment and Grocery Store*. Fac\ntories and Brewery Comprise a Part\nof Their Loot\u2014Twenty Mexican Civ\nilians Executed.\nEl Paso, Tex. \u2014Americana. Germans\nand Spanish, who arrived from Chi\nhuahua. report that Francisco Villa,\nthe rebel leader, virtually had con\natituted himself dictator there and\nthat he refused to heed th\u00b0 requests\nof the representatives of foreign gov\nernuients. They asserted that the\nrebel leader had seized $5 000,000\nworth of property belonging to for\neigners. had put ot death about twenty\nMexican civilians, including Sergeic\nSanchez, a lawyer and former state\nofficial, and had commanded the Amer\nican, German and Hritish consuls to\nobey rebel orders\nThe happenings in t\u2019hihuahua since\nVilla occupied the city on its evacua\ntion by the federal troops is given by\nthe refugees here, who number 1,000.\nVilla seized a large department\nstore valued at $1,500,000 and owned\nby French, German, English and Span\nish interests, but chiefly Spanish, and\nplaced in command of the store Gen\nf\u2019huo, a rebel leader He also seized\na brewery, a clothing larlory, all the\ngrocery and other stores owned by\nSpaniards, valued at $2,'>60,000. lie\ncalled a meeting of merchants of all\nnationalities and told them they must\npay him large sums of money, aggre\ngating several millions of dollars, to\nsupport the revolution. lie gave or\nders that the so called constitution\nalist money should be accepted as cur\nrency. Villa's expulsion of citizens of\nSpain, all erf whom were progressive\nmerchants, was on pain of death. He\nat first informed them that they must\nbe out of the country within five duys,\nbut later, after an appeal by Harry\nScobell, the Hritish vice consul, he\nextended the time to ten days. None\nof the Spaniards were allowed to take\naway anything except his personal ef\nfects, and they were told never to re\nturn.\nThe capture and imprisonment of\nLuis Terrazas, jr son of a rich land\nowner, was after Terrazas had sought\nrefuge in the British vice consulate\nand after the rebels had informed Mr.\nScobell they would break down the\nHritish vice consulate unless Terrazas\nwas released. Marion Letcher, the\nUnited States consul, was asked by\nthe foreigners to protect them, Mr.\nLetcher attempted to send a cipher\nmessage to the state department, but\nwan informed by Villa that no cipher\nmessage would be permitted on the\n\u2022rebel telegruph. Villa then informed\nthe foreign consuls in a body that\nthey would have to obey rebel orders.\nBIG CROWDS DEFY GUARDS.\nFlock to See the Restored Painting,\n\"Mona Lisa.\u201d\nFlorence A close examination of\nthe painting \u201cMona Lisa\" has dis\nclosed a slight abrasion on the cheek\nand a scratch on the left shoulder,\nwhich were received while the picture\nwas in the hands of Perugia.\nGreat crowds gathered at the Ufflzl\nga\"erv, where the \"Mona Lisa\" was\nexhibited Although strong cordons\nof carabineers were drnwn up around\nthe building and others guurded the\npntranee halls, the struggle of the mul\ntitude to get inside resulted in great\ndisorder Soldiers were thrust aside\nor knocked down, windows were\nsmashed and the people swept\nthrough, being forced out the exits by\nthe sumng mass 's b'bind.\nFormal Acquisition Ceremonies.\nCanea. Crete. The formal annexa\ntion of the island of Crete to Greece\nwas carried out with imposing cere\nmonials. King Constantine personal\nly ran up the Hellenic flag over the\nfort. People flocked to the capital\nfrom all parts of the island and from\nGreece and tumultuously greeted the\nking, the crown prince. Premier Veni\nzelos and the other ministers.\nCollision on Santa Fe Railway.\nFersno. Cal -Eight passengers and\nfour trainmen were injured, one of\nthe latter perhaps fatally, when the\nSanta Fe limited crashed into the rear\nend of another passenger train at\nStorey, twenty miles north of here. A\nheavy fog is said to have been the\ncause of the collision.\nPackages Rifled by Burglars.\nWallace. Idaho. \u2014Three packages of\nregistered mail, containing $5,000 each\nand about $2,000 in postotflce funds\nwere stolen from the safe of the local\npostotflce by burglars. No trace ot\nthem has yet been discovered.\nAn Aged Jeweler Dead.\nSan Francisco Col. Abraham Ah\ndrews, one of the oldest and best\nknown Jewelers in the United States,\nfounder of the Diamond palace here,\nis dead, nged 89 years. He was the\neldest Mason in California, having\nbeen 'nltiated in 1845.\nNew French Cabinet.\nParis. \u2014The new French premier,\nSenator Gaston Doun ergue, w ith the\nmembers of his cabinet, was received\nin audience by President Poincare at\n'he palace 'n the Klvse\u00ab\nDIGEST OF WORLD\u2019S\nIMPORTANT NEWS\nEPITOME OF THE BIG HAPPEN\nINGS OF THE WEEK.\nTO BE READ AT A GLANCE\nMams, Both Foreign and Domestic,\nThat Have Intereat for Busy Read\ners, Arranged and Claaalflad\nfor Thalr Convenience.\nWashington\nAndrew Carnegie takes little stock\nin rumors of business depression,\neither present or impending At th\"\nWhite House in Washington when\nasked what he thought of the general\nbusiness outlook, Mr Carnegie said:\n\"The recent reports of impending\nwidespread business depression are\nail tom my rot.\u201d\n\nThe administration currency bill\nwas subjected to many attacks dur\ning the debate In the senate at Wash\nington.\n0\nA sweeping Investigation of transit\nrates on live stock over railroads in.\nwestern classification territory was\nordered by the interstate commerce\ncommission at Washington.\nt\n0 0 0\nMountain lauirel is proposed as the\nofficial national flower of the United\nStates in a bill introduced in the\nhouse at Washington by Representa\ntive Kinkead of New York.\n\nPresident Wilson has taken more\ncold and canceled all his engagements\nby order of his physician. Chief ,lus\ntlce White and Justice Lurtou also aru\nconfined to their homes in Washington\nsuffering with colds.\nf I\n\nThe house at Washington was turned\ninto a circus for an honr and a half\nRepresentatives Hobson and Bartholdt\ndebated the prohibition question be\nfore crowded galleries. Underwood\nrose repeatedly to c harge Mr. Hobson\nwith misrepresenting him.\n\nGovernment ownership of telegraph\nand telephone lines is being serious\nly considered by the president. Con\nferences between the president and\nPostmaster General Hurleson at Wash\nington have led to a gathering of in\nformation about the practical work\nings of government ow nership in other\ncountries.\n0 0 0\nSecretary r,f War Garrison in his\nannual report said the time had not\nyet come for disarming or slackening\nthe nation's efforts for preparedness\nin case of war. He also declared the\npresent provision for an army reserve\nis not working satisfactorily.\n\nA petition for national prohibition\nby constitutional amendment was\npresented to President Wilson and\ncongress by a committee of 1,000.\n0 0 0\nCounsel for Margaret Catherine Sul\nlivan. seventeen years old, obtained\nfrom the supreme court an order to\ncompromise for $50,000 her claim\nagainst the estate of Representative\nTimothy D. Sullivan, Tammany leader.\nIt had not been known until this ac\ntion was taken that \"Big Tim\" had a\ndaughter.\n0 0 0\nThe report of the house lobby inves\ntigating committee at Washington se\nverely censures Representative Mc-\nDonald and asserts that the National\nAssociation of Manufacturers and oth\ner organizations have maintained an\nimproper lobby in Washington. It\ndoes not recommend or suggest any\naction by congress upon these find\nings.\n0 0 0\nWhere President Wilson will spend\nhis Christmas vacation, if he takes\none, will be left to the \"Main House.\"\nThis is the president's way of saying\nMrs Wilson and the Misses Wilson\nwill make the selection.\n0 0 0\nDomestic\nWith its starboard main-shaft pro\npeller broken and several of its com\npartments flooded, the battleship Ver\nmont is on its way toward Hampton\nroads on the return trip from the\nMediterranean cruise. It is under\nconvoy of the battleship Delaware and\nthe colliers Orion and Jason.\nThe Harvard seniors at Cambridge.\nMass have elected a negro, Alexan\nder L. Jackson of Englewood, N. J\u201e\ntheir orator for class day, 1914.\nJoseph Anderson was shot and\nkilled by Mamie Lindsey at I.*n\ncaster. Pa. It is said that the dead\nmau w\u2019as jealous of his son, who\nhad ecllpstwl him in Winning the af\nfections of the woman. She was ar\nrested.\ni\nA bomb delivered in the office of\nthe O. K. Bottling company, 528-SJIO\nWest Thirty-eighth street, New York,\nexploded und killed an eighteen-year\nold girl, Ida Anusewitz. Thomas Mc-\nCabe. the office manager, was fatally\nhurt.\nDeath in the electric chair for Hans\nSchmidt, the renegade priest, who\nconfessed the murder of Anna Aumul\nler, was demanded by Assistant Dis\ntrict Attorney J. A. Delahanty, in his\nopening address to the jury In New\nYork\nTHE KADOKA PRESS;- KADOKA, SOUTH DAKOTA.\nThe motorcycle corps of the .New\nYork police department of 23 men has\nI arrested more than 13,000 persons In\nthe last year. The total of fines Im\nposed has been over $117,000.\nPere Marquette railroad was fined\n$6,100 and the Wabash assessed SIOO\nby Judge Arthur J. Tuttel In the United\nStates court at Detroit, Mich., the for\nmer for failure to obey In full the fed\neral railroad laws, and the latter for\nthe violation of the safety appliance\nlaw\nf\u2022\nSheriff Smith of Bingham, Utah, re\nfused to grant the request of Mrs W\n3 Coo and Mrs Alvida M. O. Carlz,\nwho asked that they be permitted to\nenter the Utah-Apex mine and try to\nj induce Ralph Lopez, Mexican deeper\nado and slayer of six men, to surren\nder\n0 0 0\nAthur Schwlchow is on his way\nfrom Nashville, Tenn., to Wheaton,\nHI., to face a charge of murder for\nthe killing of Edmund Rotermund\nassistant cashier of the Addison State\nbank, October 25. Cecil Baker, w host\nfriendship for Schwlchow brought\nabout his arrest, has been held as an\naccessory.\n\nCharges that the American Tele\nphone and Telegraph company, the\nCentral Union Telephone company and\nthe Chicago Telephone company con\nspired to wreck the Interstate com\npany and drive it from the competing\nfield in Illinois, were made in a bill\nfiled In the circuit court on behalf of\n78 bondhoj\u00a3-rs of the Interstate com\npany.\n\nAfter an all-night search Sheriff\nRussell raptured three suspects for\nsafe blowing at Lawler, la. The men\nhad $l6O in money, many gold rings\nand a complete outfit of burglar tools.\n0 0 0\nThe Safety and Sanitation confer\nence opened In New York and the\nspeakers said that while great strides\nhave been made In the last decade in\nthe direction of safety for shop work\ners, there is much yet to be done\n0 0 0\nMexican Revolt\nHead Admiral Fletcher, commander\nof the American naval forces in Mex\nican waters, ordered the rebels and\nfederals fighting at Tampico to cease\nfiring, threatening to open upon them\nwith the guns of the gunboat Wheel\ning if his order was not obey. Both\nsides obeyed.\n\nAmericans who arrived at El Paso,\nTex., from Chihuahua reported that\nsince their occupation of that city the\nrebels had entered the British vice\nconsulate and forcibly seized Luis Ter\nrazas, Jr., a son of the wealthiest land\nowner in Mexico and placed him in\njail.\n\nThe Mexican congress nullified the\nrecent presidential election. New\nelections were called. In voting that\nthe presidential election of October\n26 was null the deputies decided to\nfix the first Sunday in July, 1914, as\nthe date for the new election. They\nalso confirmed the position of Huerta\nas provisional president until then.\n\nForeign\nThe Russian government proposed\nthe withdrawal of all fooeign troops\nfrom Peking and the entire province\nof Chi-Li, China, including the lega\ntion guards, the regiments at Tientsin\nan\u2019l the troops guarding the railway\nbetween the sea and Peking. Russia\nconsiders conditions in the north of\nChina no longer dangerous to foreign\ners.\n\nA newspaper advertising campaign\nfor recruits to the British army is to\nbe undertaken in all parts of Great\nBritain. The war office has become\nconvinced of the value of the news\npapers as a medium.\n\n\u201cMona Lisa,\" da Vinci\u2019s\nmasterpiece, the mysterious dlsap\npearance of which from the Louvre\nin August, 1911, threw the art world\ninto consternation, was found in Flor\nence, Italy. The man who stole It was\narrested.\n\nGreat excitement w r as caused on the\nbourse at Madrid, Spain, by the fail\nure of the Banko Hlspano-Amerlcano,\na $20,000,000 institution, to open its\ndoors.\n\ns\nJohn Holloway, vice-chairman of\nthe port docks board, was shot during\na riot between nonunion coal men and\nstrikers at Dublin.\nLeon Letort, a well known French\naviator, was killed at Barbezieux, De\npartment of Charente, France. July\n14 Letort made a record nonstop\nflight of 590 miles from Paris to Ber\nlin in eight hours.\nMiss Helen Goudy of Chicago, noted\nbeauty of the American colony, be\ncame the bride of Lieut. Gerard Leigh\nof the First Life guards. The wed\nding took place in St. George's Hau\nover square, London.\nThe city council of Pari*, France, re\njected the proposal to restore sisters\nof charity and the members of other\nnursing orders to the posts they held\nin the Paris hospitals prior to the sep\naration of church and state.\nPersonal\nWilliam Astor Chanler, African ex\nplorer and author, is suffering in\nParis. France, from injuries sustained\nin an automobile accident ten day*\nago. An operation on one of his legs\nwill be necessary.\nHUNTERS PAY FEES\nLARGE NUMBER OF SPORTSMEN\nCAME TO SOUTH DAKOTA IN\nSEARCH OF GAME\nOTHER ITEMS OF INTEREST\nFrom the Capitol City, the Various\nState Institutions and From\nMany Different Parts of\nthe Sunshine State.\nPierre. \u2014Reports made by county\nofficers to the state game department\nshow that up to November 1 there\nhad been issued in the sfate 22,966\nresident hunters\u2019 licenses at $1 each,\nthe greatest demand being in the\ncounties of Brown, Codiifgton, Law\nrence and Minnehaha, each of which\nissued over 1,000 such licenses. Only\n36 big game licenses were taken out\nup to that time, all of these being in\nthe counties of the western part of\nthe state.\nThere were 207 licenses issued to\nnon-resident hunters of feathered\ngame, Day county granting 56 of\nthese, with Robert and Union show\ning a number of such licenses, and\nthe rest scattered over the state in\nmany counties. The non-resident\nfishing licenses only showed 78 out\nsiders taking advantage of the fishing\nprivileges, they being in the counties\nof Bon Homme, Charles Mix, Hughes,\nLawrence, Pennington, Union and\nYankton, the largest number being\nfor Union county where Sioux City\nf heremn come for their sport in that\nline, over half the licenses being for\nthat county, with Charles Mix second\nand Hughes third in the list.\nThe receipts for the months men\ntioned are:\nResident gun licenses $22,966\nNon-resident feathered game.. 3,105\nBig game licenses 180\nNon-resident fishermen 156\nState College Leads.\nMitchel.\u2014South Dakota\u2019s two lead\ning state institutions have within\nthree of the same number of regular\nstudents enrolled at the present time,\naccording to figures presented by A.\nK. Hitchcock, president of the state\nboard of regents. The university at\nVermillion has 359 students and the\nState College at Brookings has 392.\nBv a further coincidence there were\nexactly the same number of students\nenrolled at Vermillion a year ago. At\nthe university 228 of the students are\nenrolled in the college of arts and sci\nences. There are 31 seniors, 32 jun\niors, 70 sophomores and 68 freshmen.\nIn the college of law are 66 students.\nThere are 35 music students, 38 study\ning engineering and 4 medicine. In\nall there are 107 freshmen in the uni\nversity. A census taken of the 81 sen\niors graduated at Vermillion last June\nshows that 27 are practicing law, IS\nare teaching school, 11 are students\nIn law, dental and medical schools,\ntwo are\u00ab revenue collectors and two\nare traveling salesmen. Others are\nare farming, on homesteads, in stores\nand the ministry, engineering and\nteaching music. The 392 students en\nrolled at the State College are exclu\nsive of about 200 who taice the short\nagricultural course of five months.\nThere are 158 graduate, preparatory\nnnd special students, 105 freshmen, 66\nsophomores. 30 juniors and 33 seniors.\nIn the student body 68 are, studying\nagriculture, 57 home economics, 56\nmusic and 45 engineering.\nWalk is Subject of Merriment.\nAlexandria. \u2014Alexandria\u2019s chief of\npolice has lost faith in bloodhounds\nwhich are kept for the purpose of\ntracing evil doers. Several Alexandria\npeople were discussing the merits of\nthe bloodhounds, and it was decided\nto give the dogs a tryout. Money\nenough to engage the hounds was sub\nscribed. and Chief of Police Tubbicliff\nagreed to walk across country to Ful\nton, and the hounds were to trail him.\nA telephone message to Mitchell, to\nthe owner of the hounds, resulted in\nthe agreement being made. The day\nof the trial arrived, and the chief\nstarted on his \u201chike\u201d to Fulton. Then\nthe owner of the hounds was notified\nand he replied that his dogs were \u201cout\nof condition\u201d and could not come. An\nautomobile was then started after the\nchief but he had taken an irregular\nroute and could not be found until he\nwalked all the way to Fulton. He was\nmore than slightly angered when he\nlearned of the fluke.\nCommissions Issued.\nWashington.\u2014Additional fourth\nclass postmasters in South Dakota\nhave been commissioned as follows:\nLaurel, Harriet E. Johnson: Leslie,\nKatherine C. Stinson: Pierpont. I>aura\nA. Udell; Rowena, Ergen S. Houge.\nThe postoffice at Widner, Pennington\ncounty, S. D., has been discontinued.\nMail will go to Creighton.\nIncorporation Articles Filed.\nPierre. \u2014Articles of incorporation\nhave been filed for the Jefferson Bene\nvolent and Social club, Jefferson, S.\nD.; trustrees, N. I. Donnelly, J. D.\nFinley, W. G. Fountain. The Inter\nstate Land company, Watertown, cap\nital $25,000: incorporators. A. L. Jen\nkins, W. I*. McClintock, B. M. Wilson.\nt o hn N. Biber, Watertown, Brule\nftanch company, Chamberlain, capital\n$100,000; incorporators. John S. Love,\nChicago; C. W. Felton, Sioux City; H.\nF. Kegley, H. H- We3t, Scotland.\n1913 YIELD DECREASED.\nState Statistical Bureau Estimates S.\nD.\u2019s New Wealth.\nPierre. \u2014Figures of the state statisti\ncal department and fi.ose of the gov\nernment place the total production of\nwealth for South Dakota for the past\nyear at a little below that of 1912,\nwith a total of $190,991,000. The gov\nernment figures are upon agricultural\nproducts other than live stock, and\ntabulated show for the year:\nWheat 33,075,000 bu $24,045,000\nCorn, 66,810,000 bu 38,750,000\nOats, 42.294.000 bu 14,380,000\nBarley, 16,062.000 bu 8,513,000\nRye. 300,000 bu 120,000\nFlaxseed, 3,564,000 bu 4,260,000\nPotatoes, 4,602,00 bu 1,000.000\nGovernment total ~.593,867,000\nThe government estimates never in\nclude the wild hay crop of the state\nas a part of the state agricultural\nproduction, notwithstanding the fact\nthat it is a large part of the forage\ncrop, and the further fact that thou\nsands of tons are baled and shipped\nevery year, and in their crop report\nnothing is given for live stock, that\nbeing a different department of the\npublic work. The state statistical de\npartment has attempted to cover the\nfigures ignored by the government\ncollectors, and gives its figures as fol\nlows:\nVegetables and fruits 2.100.000\nHay, 2.879,000 tons 17,274 000\nDairy products 7.250.000\nPoultry and eggs 7.100,000\nLive stock 53,90\nWool and bides 1,000,000\nMinerals and stone 5>,500,000\nState department total 97,124.000\nGrand total, 1913 $100,991,000\nGrand total, 1912 199,237,00 u\nDecrease 1,246,000\nWhen it is considered that a large\nportion of the state suffered from a\nshortage of the moisture in the early\npart o? last year cutting down the\nsmall grain yield, the value of pro\nductions for the year make a good\nshowing.\nWill Investigate Hog Cholera.\nMitchell. \u2014Warfare will be inaugu\nrated against hog cholera by the com\nmercial club of Mitchell. The rav\nages of the disease among swine\nherds in this locality has cost many\nthousands of dollars, and a concerted\neffort will be made by the business\nmen through the commercial club to\ncheek the' disease. As the first step\nin the campaign plans are being made\nfor a monster farmers\u2019 mass meeting\nin Mitchell. At this time Dr. C. C.\nLipp of the South Dakota State col\nlege at Brookings, w ill be present and\nadvise the most practical methods of\nfighting the disease. The depart\nment of agriculture also has promised\nto send two of its experts to address\nthe farmers on the subject,\nsubject.\nW. C. O. F. Election.\nJefferson.\u2014The W. C. O. F. held\ntheir election of officers in their lodg9\nroom in the Authier block and the\nfollowing officers were chosen: C. It.,\nMrs. F. A. Bechard: V. C. R., Mrs. J\nB. Fountain: R. S., Mrs. L. F. Lara\nbert; F. S., Mrs. B Bernard; Treas.,\nMrs. A. S. Montagne; trustees, Mrs.\n.T. Boaubien, Mrs. E. Champaign, Mrs\nC. Montagne: delegates to the national\nconvention, Mrs. F. A. Bechard; alter\nnate, Mrs. L. F. Lambert.\nDies from Lockjaw.\nDallas. George Dengler, jr., who ac\ncidentally shot himself in the right\nshoulder with a shot gun while on his\nclc.im. 12 miles west of White river,\ndied at the Dallas hospital of lockjaw\u2019.\nIt was thought for a time after his re\nmoval to the hospital that Mr. Dengler\nwas on the road to recovery, until the\ndreaded tetanus developed. He had\nan extensive circle of friends through\nout the Rosebud country.\nK. C. Initiation at Elkton.\nElkton. Thirty-three candidates\nwere taken into Sheehan Council, No.\n1686, Knights of Columbus, at a cere\nmonial session here. Following the\nconferring of the degrees by the state\nteam a banquet was served by the wo\nmen of the Catholic church at the\nopera house. Rev. James Mangan, of\nPipestone, Minn., presided as toast\nmaster.\nIver Bagstad Dead.\nYankton. \u2014News has reached here\nof the sudden death in Minneapolis of\nIver Bagstad, for many years promi\nnent in this county, with large stores\nin Volin and Gayville, and one of the\ncounty\u2019s most substantial citizens.\nThree daughters and one son survive\nhim.\nRetail Merchants\u2019 Meeting.\nAberdeen. \u2014Arrangements axe al-\nready under way for the entertain\nment of the South Dakota Retail Mer\nchants\u2019 association in Aberdeen next\nMay. The committee in charge con\nsists of Chairman R. H. Angell. Arthur\nArnett, Martin Scliamber and H. B.\nWatkins.\nTax Sale at Oacoma.\nOacoma.\u2014Much interest was taken\nin the tax sale here. A feature was\nthe low rate of interest asked by the\nbidder, the average being 6 per cent.\nAt the sale of Todd county land a\npremium of 13 per cent is said to\nhave been paid for some of the paper.\nA term of state circuit court for\nClark county is in session at Clark,\nwitn Judge Sherwood presiding. There\nare a number of criminal cases to bo\ndisposed of.\nNEWS OF SOUTH DAKOTA.\nA. C. Brink, a leading business man\nof Pierre, is suffering from a paralytic\nstroke.\nA. J. Garner, a Madison contractor,\nwas seriously injured in a fall from a\nbuilc ng on which he was working\nat Piankinton.\nMiss Edith Strever has assumed\nthe duties of postmistress at Hammil.\nUntil recently she was teacher of a\ncountry Bchool near town.\nJohn Wilkes, of Spearfish, pleaded\nguilty o* theft when confronted with\nevidence of a trail of flour from fhe\nwarehouse to his own door.\nPaul Hempel, of Parkston, has a\ndream of a trolley driven carrier to\ntake the place of the rural mail car\nrier, the carrier to travel on tha\nroadside fence.\nGeorge Johnson, of Egan, committed\nsuicide in an old house near the rail\nroad junction south of Egan. It is\nthought that he shot himself because\nof disappointment in love.\nThe state\u2019s financial report for No\nvember, shows $523,793 in cash. $68,-\n968 of which is in general fund, $49,-\n330 in game fund, $177,685 in school\nfund which is to be distributed this\nmonth, $170,211 in twine plant fund.\nFarmers in the vicinity of Valley, in\nHyde county, are planning a rabbit\ndrive some time in the near future.\nRabbits are unusually thick this year\nand it is planned to organize two\nsides and stage a competitive drive.\nHarold Conklin, aged 22, son of a\nwell known Kingsbury county farmer,\ndied from injuries received when a\npart of a corn shelling machine he\nwas assisting in operating broke loose\nand struck him a terrible blow. He\nlived only ten minutes after being\nstruck.\nAn uncancelled check has been\nfound in Sioux Falls, drawn April 18,\n1885. payable to A. Johnson, by Arth\nur Johnson of that city. The check\nwas made out by D. W. Stites, at the\ntime deputy treasurer of Minnehaha\ncounty. It lias never passed through\nthe clearing house.\nA peculiar case is reported from\nVendon township, near Pukwana,\nwhere Alois Kepola, a well known\nfarmer, became insane as the result\nof lead poisoning. His condition was\nfound so serious that it will be neces\nsary to send him to the state hospital\nfor the insane at Yankton.\nIn the belief that a \u201cfirebug\u201d may\nhave been operating at Platte, Insur\nance Commissioner Stablen and a dep\nuty have been there investigating a re\ncent fire which destroyed the Roger\nhouse in Castalia township. The of\nficers would not discuss the nature of\nthe evidence which they had secured.\nE. A. Paulson, buttermaker at the\nWebster Co-Operative creamery, has\nreceived a silver cup, gold-lined, re\ncently awarded him by the National\nCreamery Buttermakers\u2019 association\nfor having on exhibition at the recent\nbutter show in Chicago, the highest\ntest butter exhibited from South Da\nkota.\nWhile driving in their automobile,\nG. H. Getman and family, of Mcln\ntosh were all painfully injured and the\nautomobile was rendered a total wreck\nas it dashed over a steep enbankment\non the old Wade trail near Mclntosh.\nThe machine dropped a distance of 10\nfeet while going at a good rate of\nspeed.\nRev. B. F. Tilley, for the past three\nyears pastor of the First Baptist\nchurch of Mitchell, has offered his\nresignation, to take effect March 1,\n1914. In the time that Rev. Mr. Til\nley has occupied the Mitchell pulpit\nhe has doubled the membership of the\nchurch and built a new stone struc\nture. Completion of his mission in\nMitchell is given as the reason for\nthe resignation.\nThrough a local item in the Ortley\nOutlook. F. M. Pearson, a traveling\n\u201cmedicine man\u201d known as \u201cDr. Bliss,\u201d\nfound his son from whom he had been\nseparated for many years. The son, a\nwell-to-do stock buyer at Sacred Heart,\nMinn., happened to pick up a copy of\nthe Outlook at a hotel and saw a men\ntion of his father. He communicated\nwith \u201cDr. Bliss,\u201d and a reunion of fa\nther and son followed.\nPerkins county nimrods matched\nskill recently with the/hunters of Cor\nson county, in a rabbit hunting con\ntest. When the count was made at\nthe close of a day of heroic endeavor\nthere was found to be a grand total\nof 600 jackrabbits, making two double\nwagon box loads. The average kill\nper man from Corson county exeeded\nthat of the Perkins county sportsmen\nand the latter paid for an oyster sup\npe and a dance.\nAndrew Marsh, of Vanderbilt, a pio\nneer of the Dakota territory dating\nback to the time of the civil war, died\nat Aberdeen from the complications\nresulting from several years\u2019 sickness.\nMarsh came to Dakota driving a herd\nof cattle for the use of the soldiers\nat Fort Lincoln. He was then various\nly engaged at wood cutting, stock rais\ning and prospecting along the Mis\nsouri river and in the Black Hill until\nhe retired eight years ago.\nThe arrival at. Winner of a number\nof officials of the Northwestern Rail\nroad company, and their inspection of\nthe region west of Winner, has given\nrise to the rumor that the company\ncontemplates an early extension to\nCarter and pornts in Mellette county.\nRev. G. M. Peacock, for some time\npastor of the Cottonwood Congrega\ntional church, has accepted a call to\nth\u00a3 pastorate of the Congregational\nchurch at Cass Lake and Wvmore,\nMine. He expects to assume his new\nduties there the first Sunday in Jan\nua> r.","height":"34616","width":"24204"}}
